By <a href="#Chambersodd" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Chambersodd">[Chambersodd]</a>, $D_{\theta, k}(E)\equiv \det(B_{\theta,k,\ell}-E) = 0$ if and only if $\widetilde\Delta(E) = 4 (-1)^{(q+1)/2} \sin(2 \pi q \theta) \cos(k q)$. Thus, $\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta})$ is the preimage of $[-4|\sin(2 \pi q \theta)|, 4|\sin(2 \pi q \theta)|]$ under the mapping $\widetilde\Delta(E)$. If $\theta=m/(2q)$, $m\in\mathbb Z$, $\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \frac{m}{2q}})$ is a collection of $q$ points where $\widetilde\Delta(E)=0$. (In this case, $b_0(m/(2q))=0$, so that $\widetilde H$ splits into the direct sum of an infinite number of copies of a $q$-dimensional matrix.) We note that the spectra $\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta})$ for different $\theta$ are nested in one another as $\theta$ grows from $0$ to $1/(4q)$; in particular, for each $\theta \in [0, 1)$, $$\label{eq5}
\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta})=\widetilde\Delta^{-1}([-4|\sin(2 \pi q \theta)|, 4|\sin(2 \pi q \theta)|]) 
 \subseteq \sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta = \frac{1}{4 q}})=\widetilde\Delta^{-1}([-4, 4]).$$ This implies that all the maxima of $\widetilde\Delta(E)$ are no less than 4, and all the minima are no greater than $-4$. Moreover, taking the union over all $\theta \in [0, 1)$ gives: $$\widetilde{S}\left(\frac{p}{q} \right) =\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta = \frac{1}{4 q}})=\widetilde\Delta^{-1}([-4, 4]).$$ Clearly, it is sufficient to consider only $\theta\in [0,1/(4q)]$.

<u>Case II: q is even.</u> This case is similar to case I, so we omit some details for brevity. By <a href="#Chamberseven" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Chamberseven">[Chamberseven]</a>, $D_{\theta, k}(E) = 0$ if and only if $\widetilde\Delta(E) = 4(1 - \cos(2 \pi q \theta))(1 + (-1)^{q/2}\cos(k q))$. Considering the cases $k=0, \frac{\pi}{q}$, it is easy to see that $\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta})$ is the preimage of $[0, 8 - 8 \cos(2 \pi q \theta)]$ under the mapping $\widetilde\Delta(E)$. If $\theta=m/q$, $m\in\mathbb Z$, $\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \frac{m}{q}})$ is a collection of $q$ points where $\widetilde\Delta(E)=0$. We note that the spectra $\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta})$ for different $\theta$ are nested in one another as $\theta$ grows from $0$ to $1/(2q)$; in particular, for each $\theta \in [0, 1)$, $$\label{eq14}
\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta})=\widetilde\Delta^{-1}([0, 8 - 8 \cos(2 \pi q \theta)]) 
 \subseteq \sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta = \frac{1}{2 q}})=\widetilde\Delta^{-1}([0, 16]).$$ This implies that all the maxima of $\widetilde\Delta(E)$ are no less than 16, and all the minima are no greater than 0. Moreover, taking the union over all $\theta \in [0, 1)$ gives: $$\widetilde{S}\left(\frac{p}{q} \right) =\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta = \frac{1}{2 q}})=\widetilde\Delta^{-1}([0, 16]).$$ Clearly, it is sufficient to consider only $\theta\in [0,1/(2q)]$.

In particular, $$\label{eq8}
\left| \widetilde{S}\left(\frac{p}{q}\right) \right|=|\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta = \frac{1}{4 q}})|
\leq 4\min_{\ell}\left|b_{\ell+q-1}\left(\frac{1}{4q}\right)\right|=4\cdot 2 \left| \sin2 \pi \left(\frac{1}{4 q}\right)\right| \leq \frac{4\pi}{q}.$$ Therefore, $| S(\frac{p_0}{q_0}) | = | \widetilde S(\frac{p}{q}) | \leq \frac{4\pi}{q} = \frac{4\pi}{q_0}$, as required.

<u>Case II: q is even.</u> This case is similar to case I, so we omit some details for brevity. This time, the Lidskii equations of Theorem <a href="#thm1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm1">2</a> show that $|\widetilde{S}(\frac{p}{q})| \leq \frac{8 \pi}{q}$. Indeed, as in (<a href="#eq7" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="eq7">[eq7]</a>), we have (note the doubling of the eigenvalues for $\widetilde\Delta(E)=0$) $$\label{eq12}
|\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta})| \leq 4\min_{\ell}|b_{\ell+q-1}(\theta)|.$$

In particular, $$\label{eq15}
\left| \widetilde{S}\left(\frac{p}{q}\right) \right|=|\sigma(\widetilde{H}_{\frac{p}{q}, \theta = \frac{1}{2 q}})|
\leq 4\min_{\ell}\left|b_{\ell+q-1}\left(\frac{1}{2q}\right)\right|=4\cdot 2 \left| \sin2 \pi \left(\frac{1}{2 q}\right)\right| \leq \frac{8\pi}{q}.$$ Therefore, $| S(\frac{p_0}{q_0}) | = | \widetilde S(\frac{p}{q}) | \leq \frac{8\pi}{q} = \frac{4\pi}{q_0}$, as required.

This completes the proof of Theorem <a href="#Thm1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Thm1">1</a>.
